<exercise xml:id="reading-question-de-morgans-laws" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>
    De Morgan's laws
  </title>
  
  <idx>
    De Morgan's laws
  </idx>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Let <m> S </m>, <m> T </m>, and <m> U </m> be sets.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that <m> S \setminus \of{ T \cap U } = \of{ S \setminus T } \cup \of{ S \setminus U } </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        asdf
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove that <m> S \setminus \of{ T \cup U } = \of{ S \setminus T } \cap \of{ S \setminus U } </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    
    <solution>
      <p>
        asdf
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>
  
  <conclusion>
    <p>
      Taken together, these results are called <term> De Morgan's laws </term>.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
</exercise>
